Interview Questions

Q1. What is ArrayList in Java? What are the various methods provided by it?
-->What is ArrayList?

    ArrayList is a resizable (dynamic) array implementation of the List interface in the Java Collections Framework. It maintains insertion order, allows duplicate and null elements, and provides fast random access using indexes.
    
    Syntax:
    
    ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

Common Methods of ArrayList :
    | Method                  | Description                                  |
    | ----------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
    | `add(E e)`              | Adds an element to the end.                  |
    | `add(int index, E e)`   | Inserts an element at a specific index.      |
    | `get(int index)`        | Returns the element at the specified index.  |
    | `set(int index, E e)`   | Replaces the element at the specified index. |
    | `remove(int index)`     | Removes an element by index.                 |
    | `remove(Object o)`      | Removes the specified object.                |
    | `size()`                | Returns the number of elements.              |
    | `isEmpty()`             | Checks whether the list is empty.            |
    | `contains(Object o)`    | Checks if an element exists.                 |
    | `clear()`               | Removes all elements.                        |
    | `indexOf(Object o)`     | Returns the first occurrence index.          |
    | `lastIndexOf(Object o)` | Returns the last occurrence index.           |
    | `toArray()`             | Converts the list into an array.             |
    | `iterator()`            | Returns an iterator to traverse the list.    |


Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

        list.add("Java");
        list.add("Python");
        list.add("Java");

        System.out.println(list.get(1));
        System.out.println(list.size());
    }
}




Q2. How would you convert an ArrayList to an Array and an Array to an ArrayList?
-->1. ArrayList to Array

    Use the toArray() method.
    
    import java.util.*;
    
    public class Demo {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
    
            list.add("A");
            list.add("B");
    
            String[] arr = list.toArray(new String[0]);
    
            System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));
        }
    }



2. Array to ArrayList

Use Arrays.asList().

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] arr = {"Java", "Python", "C"};

        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(arr));

        System.out.println(list);
    }
}




Q3. How does ArrayList work internally in Java, and how does it grow dynamically when elements are added?
-->Internal Working
      ArrayList internally uses an array (Object[]) to store elements.
      Initially, the internal array is empty.
      When elements are added and the array becomes full, a new larger array is created.
      Existing elements are copied into the new array, and the old array is discarded.
      Growth Process
      
      Suppose the capacity is 10.
      
      When the 11th element is added:
      
      Old Capacity = 10
      
      New Capacity = 10 + (10 / 2)
                   = 15
      
      Formula:
      
      New Capacity = Old Capacity + (Old Capacity / 2)
      
      So the capacity increases by 50%.
      
      

Q4. What is the initial capacity of the ArrayList and the default capacity of the ArrayList?
-->There are two commonly discussed capacities:
| Type             | Capacity                                     |
| ---------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Initial Capacity | 0 (empty internal array)                     |
| Default Capacity | 10 (created when the first element is added) |

Example:

ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

Initially, no memory for 10 elements is allocated.

When the first element is added, Java creates an internal array with a capacity of 10.






Q5. Can you store null values in an ArrayList?
-->Yes.

ArrayList allows multiple null values.

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

        list.add(null);
        list.add("Java");
        list.add(null);

        System.out.println(list);
    }
}

Output : 

[null, Java, null]





Q6. How can you make an ArrayList immutable?
-->An immutable ArrayList cannot be modified after creation.

    Method 1 (Recommended)
    List<String> list = List.of("Java", "Python", "C");
    
    Trying to add elements throws : UnsupportedOperationException


    Method 2
    List<String> list =  Collections.unmodifiableList(new ArrayList<>());
    
    This creates a read-only view of the list.




Q7. Is ArrayList synchronized in Java? If not, how can you make an ArrayList synchronized?
-->No.
    
    ArrayList is not synchronized, so it is not thread-safe.
    
    Method 1
    
    Use:
    
    List<String> list = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());
    Method 2
    
    Use Vector, which is synchronized by default.





Q8. What are the real-time use cases of ArrayList in Java, and when should it be used?
-->Real-Time Use Cases
      Student records
      Employee management systems
      Product lists in e-commerce applications
      Shopping cart items
      Search results
      Movie or music playlists
      Customer details
      Attendance management
      Online booking systems
      When Should You Use ArrayList?
      
      Use ArrayList when:
      
      Frequent searching or retrieval is required.
      Random access using indexes is needed.
      The collection size changes dynamically.
      Insertions and deletions mostly happen at the end.
      Duplicate elements are allowed.



Q9. What are the advantages and disadvantages of ArrayList?
-->Advantages
      Dynamic size.
      Fast random access (O(1)).
      Maintains insertion order.
      Allows duplicate elements.
      Allows null values.
      Easy to use with built-in methods.
  Disadvantages
      Slow insertion/deletion in the middle (O(n)).
      Not synchronized.
      Uses more memory due to dynamic resizing.
      Stores objects only (primitives require wrapper classes).



Q10. How many constructors are present in ArrayList?
-->ArrayList provides three constructors.
        
        1. Default Constructor
              ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
              
              Creates an empty ArrayList with default capacity allocated when the first element is added.
        
        2. Constructor with Initial Capacity
              ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>(20);
              
              Creates an ArrayList with an initial capacity of 20.
        
        3. Constructor with Collection
              List<String> names = List.of("Java", "Python");
              
              ArrayList<String> list =
              new ArrayList<>(names);
              
              Creates an ArrayList containing all elements from the specified collection.
              
              Interview Tip
              
              A common interview question is:
              
              Why is ArrayList faster than LinkedList for retrieving elements?
              
              Answer: Because ArrayList stores elements in a contiguous array, it provides O(1) random access using indexes, 
              whereas LinkedList must traverse nodes sequentially, resulting in O(n) access time.
